    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="letter">
                <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_33_2_1809_07_05_page01.jpg"/>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline> 
                        <note>11</note>
                        <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE">Edgeworths Town</placeName>
                        <date when="1809-07-05">July 5<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1809</date></dateline></opener>
                
                        <p>
                    
                        My dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DumoE1">Sir</persName><lb/>
                        You see, that I do not trouble you with<lb/>
                        frequent letters - your last I could <choice><orig>an-<lb/>
                        swer</orig><reg>answer</reg></choice> only like Echo, for it contained <choice><orig>al-<lb/>
                        most</orig><reg>almost</reg></choice> verbatim my own sentiments as they<lb/>
                        have been delivered in public and private.<lb/></p>
                        <p>
                        Your proposed method of <choice><orig>pay-<lb/>
                        ing</orig><reg>paying</reg></choice> schoolmasters is, in its principle, the<lb/>
                        same as that, which I had recommended<lb/>
                        except that I would have had part of the salary certain<lb/>
                        in this <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IE">country,</placeName> in parliament in the year<lb/>
                        1798, and since at the Board of Education<lb/>
                        - You have I hope seen our reports? The last<lb/>
                        on "Wilson's Hospital" the Board did me the<lb/>
                        honor to commit to my hands; it was sent<lb/>
                    
                        <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_33_2_1809_07_05_page02.jpg"/>
                         before parliament was prorogued, but I am<lb/>
                         not sure, that it arrived in time to be <choice><orig>print-<lb/>
                         ed.</orig><reg>printed</reg></choice> - I trouble you at present<lb/>
                         to inform me whether my good, but <choice><orig>care-<lb/>
                         -less</orig><reg>careless</reg></choice> publisher <persName ref="./Personography.xml#JohnJ1">Johnson</persName> has sent you <title ref="./Workography.xml#Essay3">"Essays<lb/>
                         on Professional Education",</title> which I begged<lb/>
                         he would present to you from the author<lb/>
                         If he has not I shall be much displeased<lb/>
                         with him, for I wished, that it should reach<lb/>
                         you before the book should be published.<lb/></p>
                        <p>
                         In <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria's</persName> <title ref="./Workography.xml#Taleo1">"Tales of fashionable life"</title><lb/>
                         you will recognise in Madame de Fleury<lb/>
                         the charming <persName ref="./Personography.xml#PastA1">Madame Pastoret</persName> at whose<lb/>
                         house we first had the pleasure of meeting<lb/>
                         you. My <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">daughter</persName> takes singular <choice><orig>plea-<lb/>
                         -sure</orig><reg>pleasure</reg></choice> in recording generous actions and<lb/>
                         she was peculiarly desirous of paying<lb/>
                    
                          <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_33_2_1809_07_05_page03.jpg"/>
                          <note>12</note>
                          a tribute of gratitude to one of the many<lb/>
                          friends at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Paris_FR">Paris</placeName> who shewed us real<lb/>
                         <hi rend="underline">friendship</hi> in the most comprehensive<lb/>
                          English acceptation of the word - Do me<lb/>
                          the favor to repeat to us an anecdote of<lb/>
                          a servant &amp; child of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#PastA1">Madame Pastorets</persName><lb/>
                          which you told to our friend <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WellC1" cert="high">Lady Wellesley</persName><lb/></p>
                          <closer>
                          I am Dear Sir<lb/>
                          Your faithful Servant<lb/>
                          <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1">Rich<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>Lovell Edgeworth</persName><lb/></closer>
                
            </div>
        </body>
